title: Parametric Y-Axis Back Brace for 8", 10" or 12" Prusa i3v

description.text:
Update Rev5 2/11/2016
I corrected a mirror problem that pgx3d spotted. I also added 8" & 12 test parts & updated them so the bottom side of them should line up with the back of the Y-axis Wood Plate. While working on a plastic design of the Y-axis backplate for the i3v this idea came about after talking with my friend voodoo28 and his problem with the 12" version flexing. I like making parametric designs, so I went ahead & made this design so you could make a brace for either the 8", 10" or 12" i3v. I have the 10" version and have not experienced this problem. this is probably only needed for the 12" version & is untested, but seems like it should work. If you are interested in trying this, I would print the test stl file for the i3v version you are using to make sure the bolt holes line up 1st, before printing main part. I tested the 10" version & it lines up for that. It took me 33 minutes to print the test part for the 10" using 20%infill & 2 solid layers for top & bottom. The final part with 50% infill would probably take about 2 hours to print. The test prints have the holes the diameter of the bolt heads. That way the test print should fit flat against the back of the y-axis plate if they are lined up right. The dimensions for the 8" i3v I got from Colin, so they should also be correct. The 12" version I got from:
https://github.com/DonKahones/MakerFarm-Prusa-i3v-12-Inch I included a test stl for each i3v version, and final stl file for each i3v as well as an openscad file you can change to make it a thicker or thinner brace & bigger or smaller ledge in the middle. There are 5 variables specific to which i3v you are using, just comment out the variables the versions you are not using. Here are the ones for the 12" version
i3v = 12;
i3v_Width = 346.5; //12" i3v = 346.5mm
i3v_Vslot_Width = 238.8; //12" i3v = 238.68 or 238.8
i3v_Vslot_Offset = 63.5; //12" i3v = 63.5
i3v_MotorOffset = 166.6; //12" i3v = 166.6 This brace in its current size is 6mm thick & 2mm countersink for bolts, so your bolts will have to be 4mm longer. That is you will have to replace the current two M3x16 bolts with M3x20 & the two M5x12 bolts with M5x16.

title: HICTOP Prusa i3 Bed leveling nuts holder and spring tensioner

description.text:
These are intended to be used on the HICTOP Prusa i3 sheet-metal beds.
  • Makes leveling the bed much easier using a Philips screw driver
  • Holds the nuts in place and prevent them from coming undone and falling off (no more annoying rabbit ear or the thumb screw coming lose and falling off in the middle of the print rabbit-ears)
  • adds tension to the springs and also hugs the bottom half of the spring to reduce bed vibration. The spring can compress and decompress and is more restricted to move in any other direction. It should theoretically reduce the y-axis wobble, but I am still unsure by how much.
    • Note: I have tested printing this in both ABS and PLA, however I get much better results when printed in ABS. it seems to hold on to the nut better and is also an all around better fit. You also want your spring to fit in there quite tightly, yet it should be able to compress and decompress relatively freely in order to hold up the bed. if it is too tight to fit on the edge of the bed (interestingly some the regular one will fit some corners, but may not fit other corners because the sheet metal is not exactly accurately shaped or it bends under normal use) use the "Wide" one.

This is a "2 in 1" upgrade for Any cheap Kossel/Delta with 20x20x680mm long vertical extrusions/rods. These printers often comes with low quality rods, and getting 3 good quality replacement should cost you from about 25 to 60 bucks depending on where you buy/order them. With this upgrade, you not only get better prints thanks to your printer being enhanced with 3 smoother rods, but you also stabilize your printer a lot with reusing the original rods for stability. The spared old rods will reinforce each corner of the printer using an angle of 7°. Prerequisites
  • 680mm tall 20x20 based delta printer
  • The model using 9 identical plastic corners for the frame, 2 of them being used for each 3 axis steppers (Bottom parts attach between them). Versions using a single taller attach for the axis steppers needs another design for fixation.
    • For your convenience, I created a Corner set and a Full set. The first one will cover one of the 3 corners, the second one should let you print everything needed at once.
Notes: I used 33% infill full honeycomb in simplify3D, 2 shells. PLA is just fine. I woudl probably go up to 50% infill if linear. Feel free to do more :-)

For each rod, you'll need 1 7Bottom, 1 7Top and 1 7Feet, but also 6 bolts, 6 washers and 6 nuts that fits your 20x20 extrusion type (Square nuts or T-nuts). First, I suggest you "get a feel" of how easy the printer top can oscillate horizontally, so you'll be able to compare after the upgrade Instructions to repeat 3 times for each corner: 1) Print the parts;
2) Add a bolt, a washer and a nut (only for a few turns) to the extremity that fits the main frame on 7bottom, do the same on 7top;
3) Now do the same to the side holes that will secure the new rod;
4) Attach 7top to the main frame approximatly 1 to 2 cm lower than the top angle plastic part;
5) Attach 7bottom to the main frame between the two bottom angle plastic parts;
6) Plug 7feet to the bottom of the new rod. (if calibration is ok, the rod should slide through 7bottom and 7top even when the feet is added, if not, plus the feet at the end);
7) Slide the new rod through the holes of the two attached parts. Ensure it rests perfectly leveled with the printer itself, then secure it. Now. if you did what I suggested before, try again, and tell me if you're happy :-)

title: Split X-Ends for i3  with Leadscrew & cable ties - parametric

description.text:
Enif's design is really good, everything gets oriented so the end part is the strongest it can be. I needed one for Z-leadscrews and cable ties. I also rotated the endstop so it can print without support (other parts may still require support depending on your printer). Enif's original: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:514582,
Also inspired by 3ed_de's addition of cable ties (zip ties) http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:894915 The OpenSCAD has the z-leadscrew and cable tie code are in the .scad file. It's called "ziptieCavities" in case you want to get rid of the cable tie holes. For the Idler bearing holder or the endstop, it's easiest to get it from Enif's original: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:514582 Thanks for Enif for this, I really learned a lot about OpenSCAD on this project.

Notes: see Enif's original: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:514582 I'm currently printing my own verison of this in PETG and it seems to be much more dimensionally stable than the PLA I used earlier, the PLA shrank noticably ove the last few months.

comments.text: I'm in the process of printing these right now. They look amazing. There's just one thing- as the leadscrew passes through the printed part, it comes in contact with the part that is for clamping the linear rods. It's the 45 degree nut trap. I will have to file a little bit of material for this to work, which is no big deal. I just thought I would let you know. Thanks!

Notes: Printed in PLA via Cura generated Gcode and Spooler on M3D. if your printer is decent at overhangs, slice/print upside down with supports on but set to minimal to prevent supports from being printed in the hole. if printing with supports, they will form around the main handle as there is small 90 degree when printed upright, and a taper on the main handle to support upside down (it's a slightly complex, pretty accurate model, not just two spheres cut in half and stuck on a central cylinder, which was what i was thinking before actually really looking at a pin for this design.). if printed upright with supports, you may have to clean up the hole for the insert to fit, depending how well your printer keeps supports seperated from the model.
To assemble after printing both pieces, put nail through the insert, and epoxy/crazy glue the insert and nail into the hole on the main piece.
Modelling Software Used: Fusion 360 Modeled to size, then scaled by 600% (actually scaled by 300%, decided that was too small, then scaled that by 200%).

title: Air-tight Single Piece Pump - Shkolnikov Pump

description.text:
Well, one printed part anyway. You still need to put in some tubing. After having some trouble with the first peristaltic pump I tried, I did some Google-ing and came across this:
http://microfluidics.stanford.edu/Publications/Micropumps_Cooling/Shkolnikov-selfpriming-rollerfree-minature-peristaltic-pump.pdf It is basically a diaphragm pump with the check valves and diaphragm integrated into a single piece of plastic. The best performing version so far can be viewed here: http://youtu.be/fRKeDQPz7xw With some more tweaking I'm sure it can be made better. The nice thing about it is that it requires very little plastic, and is very compact. In the paper they drive it with an eccentric cam. Naturally I want to make some computer-controlled colored-water tubing thing with a bunch of these now. Also, real 3d-printed squirt guns. Update: There is currently a problem with this pump that doesn't arise until a few days after assembly. Presumably due to creep, the downstream valve slowly loses its ability to seal completely, resulting in greater backflow and then failure. I will experiment but I may not be able to solve this problem without adding pieces (thinking of a set screw plunger sort of deal). Version History: V2 (11/1/2011): Improved stroke volume and reduced backflow.

(1) Print the part.
(2) Thread tubing that is soft enough to be pressed into an airtight seal. I used the following: McMaster Part Number 5236K835 (Disclaimer: Make sure liquid you are pumping is chemically compatible with tubing you use.)
(3) Complete circuit of some sort with couplings or whatever. McMaster sells the plastic ones in the video for reasonably cheap.

title: 1979 Vespa PX125 Fuel Shutoff Valve Alternative

description.text:
If you have any experience with old Vespas, you will know that it's hard to get good quality replacement parts as a lot of them are from India and aren't really good quality. Such is the fuel shut off lever for the PX125. It has a crown gear mechanism that skips easily. The means the fuel doesn't get completely shut off and it drips out, leaving you high and dry if you wait too long between rides. Not to mention wasting gas and making a puddle in your garage.   
This is simpler version that works pretty well. The current prototype is made of PLA since that's what I had set up. I think ABS would be better.
I printed with 30% infill and 100 micron layer height. Held together with M3x14 socket head cap screws.
